  "response_text": "The halting problem is a decision problem in computability theory that was introduced by Alan Turing in 1936. It asks whether, given a description of an arbitrary computer program and an input, it is possible to decide whether the program will run forever or will eventually halt when run with that input.\n\n### Formal Definition\n\nFormally, the halting problem can be stated as follows: Given a description of a program \\( P \\) and an input \\( I \\), determine whether \\( P \\) halts (terminates) on \\( I \\).\n\n### Turing's Proof\n\nTuring proved that there is no general algorithm that can solve the halting problem for all possible program-input pairs. His proof involves a diagonalization argument and a self-referential construction. Here\u2019s a simplified version of the proof:\n\n1. **Assume** there exists a program \\( H \\) that can solve the halting problem.\n2. Construct a new program \\( D \\) that uses \\(",
